solutions.content:
Firstly I am doing error checking to see if the given paragraph is empty or not. There are some important points in this code:

1) I am transferring the values in the banned vector to a set, to later on search over those words efficiently. Also since set will have unique values, we are eliminating the possibility of wating our time with the same banned words if there are any.
2) In the for loop, I am cleaning the paragraph. Since our search will be case insensitive we will have to convert all characters in the paragraph to lower case since all of the banned words are in lower case. Doing this, we will have a common ground to search over. I am also replacing any non-alphabetic character with a space. Do not forget to iterate over the characters in the paragraph by reference since we want to modify them.
3) I am utilizing input string stream to parse words from the paragraph. Note that we could also have used a simple string stream but input string stream makes our intention clearer.

```
class Solution {
public:
    string mostCommonWord(string p, vector<string>& banned) {
        if(p.empty()) return {};

        std::string res;
        std::unordered_set<string> banned_words(banned.begin(), banned.end());
        std::unordered_map<string, int> count_map;

        for (auto& ch : p) {
            ch = isalpha(ch) ? tolower(ch) : ' ';
        }

        istringstream iss(p);
        std::string word; 

        int max = INT_MIN;


        while(iss >> word) {
            if(banned_words.find(word) == banned_words.end()) {
                ++count_map[word];
                if(count_map[word] > max) {
                    max = count_map[word];
                    res = word;
                }
            }
        }

        return res;    
    }
};
```

